04938nam a22007095i 9780813541020DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2006    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135410207 a10.36019/97808135410202doi  a(DE-B1597)526243  a(OCoLC)1058894081  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0000002bisacsh1 aMurdoch, Lydia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.10aImagined Orphans :bPoor Families, Child Welfare, and Contested Citizenship in London /cLydia Murdoch. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2006] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b24 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRutgers Series in Childhood Studies00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1. "A Little Waif of London, Rescued from the Streets ": Melodrama and Popular Representations of Poor Children -- t2. From Barrack Schools to Family Cottages: Creating Domestic Space and Civic Identity for Poor Children -- t3. The Parents of "Nobody's Children": Family Backgrounds and the Causes of Poverty -- t4. "That Most Delicate of All Questions in an Englishman's Mind": The Rights of Parents and Their Continued Contact with Institutionalized Children -- t5. Training "Street Arabs" into British Citizens: Making Artisans and Members of Empire -- t6. "Their Charge and Ours": Changing Notions of Child Welfare and Citizenship -- tConclusion -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX -- tABOUT THE AUTHOR0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith his dirty, tattered clothes and hollowed-out face, Oliver Twist is the enduring symbol of the young indigent spilling out of orphanages and haunting the streets of late-nineteenth-century London. Although poor children were often portrayed as real-life Oliver Twists-either orphaned or abandoned by unworthy parents-they in fact frequently maintained contact and were eventually reunited with their families. In Imagined Orphans, Lydia Murdoch focuses on this discrepancy between the representation and the reality of children's experiences within welfare institutions-a discrepancy that she argues stems from conflicts over middle- and working-class notions of citizenship that arose in the 1870s and persisted until the First World War. Reformers' efforts to depict poor children as either orphaned or endangered by abusive or "no-good" parents fed upon the poor's increasing exclusion from the Victorian social body. Reformers used the public's growing distrust and pitiless attitude toward poor adults to increase charity and state aid to the children. With a critical eye to social issues of the period, Murdoch urges readers to reconsider the complex situations of families living in poverty. While reformers' motivations seem well intentioned, she shows how their methods solidified the public's antipoor sentiment and justified a minimalist welfare state that engendered a cycle of poverty. As they worked to fashion model citizens, reformers' efforts to protect and care for children took on an increasingly imperial cast that would continue into the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813541020423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813541020.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBA